04231nam a22004815i 9780300160901DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t19791979ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001609017 a10.12987/97803001609012doi  a(DE-B1597)486715  a(OCoLC)1024049041  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aREL0000002bisacsh1 aFranklin, Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Origins of Christian Morality /cBenjamin Franklin; Ralph L. Ketcham, Leonard W. Labaree. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[1979] 4cÂ©1979  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter I. Morals And Community -- tChapter 2. Turning: Moral Consequences Of Conversion -- tChapter 3. City, Household, People Of God -- tChapter 4. Loving And Hating The World -- tChapter 5. The Language Of Obligation -- tChapter 6. The Grammar Of Christian Practice -- tChapter 7. Knowing Evil -- tChapter 8. The Body As Sign And Problem -- tChapter 9. A Life Worthy Of God -- tChapter 10. Senses Of An Ending -- tChapter 11. The Moral Story -- tPostscript. History, Pluralism, And Christian Morality -- tNotes -- tBibliography Of Secondary Works Cited -- tIndex Of Early Christian Literature -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy the time Christianity became a political and cultural force in the Roman Empire, it had come to embody a new moral vision. This wise and eloquent book describes the formative years-from the crucifixion of Jesus to the end of the second century of the common era-when Christian beliefs and practices shaped their unique moral order. Wayne A. Meeks examines the surviving documents from Christianity's beginnings (some of which became the New Testament) and shows that they are largely concerned with the way converts to the movement should behave. Meeks finds that for these Christians, the formation of morals means the formation of community; the documents are addressed not to individuals but to groups, and they have among their primary aims the maintenance and growth of these groups. Meeks paints a picture of the process of socialization that produced the early forms of Christian morality, discussing many factors that made the Christians feel that they were a single and "chosen" people. He describes, for example, the impact of conversion; the rapid spread of Christian household cult-associations in the cities of the Roman Empire; the language of Christian moral discourse as revealed in letters, testaments, and "moral stories"; the rituals, meetings, and institutionalization of charity; the Christians' feelings about celibacy, sex, and gender roles; and their sense of the end-time and final judgment. In each of these areas Meeks seeks to determine what is distinctive about the Christian viewpoint and what is similar to the moral components of Greco-Roman or Jewish thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aKetcham, Ralph L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLabaree, Leonard W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package Archivez978311053801440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300160901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300160901.jpg  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles